#Use kubectl commands to create, scale, and manage Kubernetes resources like pods and deployments.


✅ Step 0 – Start Kubernetes (Minikube)


minikube start
kubectl get nodes

✔ Output should show:

NAME       STATUS   ROLES    AGE   VERSION
minikube   Ready    control-plane


🚀 Step 1 – Create Deployment


kubectl create deployment myapp --image=nginx:latest

✔ Check output


kubectl get deployments

Example:

NAME    READY   UP-TO-DATE   AVAILABLE
myapp   1/1     1            1
kubectl get pods

Example:

NAME                     READY   STATUS    RESTARTS
myapp-xxxxxx-abcde       1/1     Running   0


📈 Step 2 – Scale Deployment
🔹 Scale up to 3


kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=3
kubectl get pods

✔ Output:

3 pods running
🔹 Scale down to 1


kubectl scale deployment myapp --replicas=1
kubectl get pods

✔ Output:

1 pod running
🌐 Step 3 – Expose Service


kubectl expose deployment myapp --port=80 --type=NodePort


✔ Check service
kubectl get services

Example:

NAME    TYPE       PORT(S)
myapp   NodePort   80:30007
🌍 Open in browser

minikube service myapp

✔ This opens nginx page in browser

🔍 Step 3 – Inspect & Logs


Get pod name
kubectl get pods
Describe pod
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
View logs
kubectl logs <pod-name>


🧹 Cleanup


kubectl delete deployment myapp
kubectl delete service myapp

✔ Output:

deployment "myapp" deleted
service "myapp" deleted


📄 Step 4 – Using YAML


Create file: deployment.yaml


apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: myapp
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: myapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: myapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: myapp
        image: nginx:latest
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80



Apply YAML

kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

✔ Check everything

kubectl get all

Example output:

deployment.apps/myapp
pod/myapp-xxxx Running
service/myapp






